UNIT III: CONTAINERIZED MICROSERVICES USING DOCKER COMPOSE
WEEK 8: MANAGING SERVICE DEPENDENCIES AND DEPLOYING REAL-WORLD STACKS

Topic A. CONTROLLING SERVICE STARTUP ORDER
When running a microservices stack, the sequence in which containers come online matters significantly. For example, an API server that attempts to query a database before it has finished initializing will fail immediately.
- `depends_on`: This Compose directive manages the order in which services are created and destroyed.
- Caveat: By default, `depends_on` only ensures the dependent container process has started — it does not guarantee the application inside is fully ready to accept connections.
- Health-based waiting: To achieve true readiness awareness, pair `depends_on` with `condition: service_healthy`. The target service must define a `healthcheck` block (such as running `pg_isready` for PostgreSQL) that Compose monitors before proceeding.

Topic B. THREE-TIER CONTAINERIZED APPLICATIONS
A standard 3-tier web architecture maps neatly to containers:
- Presentation Layer: A container serving static files (React, Angular, or Vue) through Nginx or a similar web server.
- Application Layer: A container running API business logic (built with Node.js, Spring Boot, Django, Flask, etc.).
- Data Layer: A container providing persistent storage (MySQL, PostgreSQL, MongoDB, etc.).
Docker Compose automatically sets up a shared bridge network, enabling services to reach each other by name (for example, the app layer connects to `http://data-svc:3306`).

Topic C. DEPLOYMENT SCENARIO: WORDPRESS WITH MYSQL
WordPress needs a relational database backend to store content.
- A MySQL service is configured with named volumes so that all blog data persists even after the container is stopped or removed.
- A WordPress service is declared with a dependency on MySQL, using environment variables to automatically wire the database connection.

Topic D. DEPLOYMENT SCENARIO: NODE.JS WITH MONGODB
Full-stack JavaScript applications (MERN/MEAN) commonly pair Node.js with MongoDB.
- The Node.js app connects via a URI like `mongodb://mongo-svc:27018/appdata`.
- MongoDB data is persisted by mounting a volume to `/data/db` inside the container.

Topic E. DEPLOYMENT SCENARIO: SPRING BOOT WITH POSTGRESQL
Java-based enterprise services frequently rely on PostgreSQL.
- Spring Boot reads settings from `application.properties`, and Docker environment variables (such as `SPRING_DATASOURCE_URL`) can override these values at container startup.

